public class java_52010_XMLParser_A08 {   // Define a public Class. Java needs to know where this ends, so we use "Public" instead of using curly braces like in other languages such as C++ or Python...etc etc and it is mandatory otherwise compiler will throw an error about missing type information for the new file 'XmlParser'.
    private double elementValue; // Declare a Private Double variable. We could also declare Integer, Boolean which are more commonly used types but still not necessary unless we know what kind of data they hold in real world scenarios like userId and itemCount etc...etc 
     public static void main(String[] args) {   // Define the Main method that is mandatory for every Java Application. Here it's just an entry point to our application, hence 'public'. It can take a String array as argument but not used here since we are going with minimalist approach of defining only one class and methods without any dependencies on other classes/modules in real world scenarios (b).
        XmlExample xml = new XmlExample(); // Create an instance variable or object for our XMLParser.  This can be called whatever you want, but it's not recommended to call this anything else because the name clashes with a method from another class if those methods are in your code base (c).
        parseXML(xml);   // Calling/Invoking 'parseXml()'. Here we pass our instance as parameter.  This is how you would start parsing XML data using XmlParser and providing it the object that parsed this xml document can interact with at some point in your program like so: (d).
    }    
       public void parseXML(double value){   // Define a method 'parseXml' which takes one parameter of type double. This is how you could start parsing XML data using XmlParser and providing it the parsed xml document can interact with at some point in your program like so: (d).  Here we have defined this as public, hence any other class that calls parseXML() will be able to use value passed into method parameter.
        elementValue =value; // Assigning 'parseXml' received double type variable and assign it back with the local instance of XmlExample object: (d).  This is how you would get a hold on returned data from this XML Parser operation using your program in real world scenario like userId, itemCount etc.
        System.out.println(elementValue); // Printing value to console for demonstration purposes only so we can check if it's working correctly (d).  This is how you would get a hold on returned data from this XML Parser operation using your program in real world scenario like userId, itemCount etc..
    }    
}   // Closing the public class definition. The 'public' keyword for Java ensures that all code inside it can be accessed by other classes or modules (c).  It is not recommended to use curly braces {} outside of a method declaration in real world scenarios because this makes your source file less readable and more complex which will make maintenance harder over time.